Most of you have seen my posts regularly and know what I do.  In the past
3  years on the Internet (since November 1991), I have engaged in selling
a  variety  of  goods  for  the  videogame market, such as used videogame
cartridges  and  videogame  cartridge  copiers.   As  a matter of fact, I
introduced  videogame  cartridge copiers (the Multi-Game Doctor 2) to the
Internet  in 1991.  During this time, I attended UC Berkeley, majoring in
Electrical   Engineering   &   Computer  Science  and  Materials  Science
Engineering.   I  graduated in June, 1993.  At the time, my email address
was lchiu@ocf.Berkeley.EDU.  <-- Do not send mail to this account!!

I  have  recently returned to Hong Kong.  Many users on the Internet have
expressed  an  interest in videogame cartridge copiers so I will continue
to  sell  these  devices  to  the American and Canadian markets.  In Hong
Kong,  I  also  have  the  benefit  of being out of Sega's and Nintendo's
reach.  <grin>

Copiers  from  me  have  traditionally  been  expensive.  (send email for
information  on  legality of videogame cartridge copiers)  I feel that it
is  a risky venture to be engaged in and demand suitable compensation for
my services.  Because of this new development, the risk has been reduced,
and  so  my  prices have been adjusted to reflect this.  In short, I have
the LOWEST prices in the entire North America (see below.)

There  are many people selling copiers on the Internet, and you should be
careful who you deal with.  No one has been around longer than I have and
I  have  dealt  honestly with literally hundreds of customers in the past
three  years.   Many  of  them  continue  to buy from me, even today.  My
record speaks for itself.

All prices are in US dollars.  Conversion factors to other currencies are
published in newspapers worldwide, in the business section.

All videogame cartridge copiers have built-in support for battery backed-
up videogames, real time save, Gold Finger, which is a feature comparable
to  Game  Genie,  and  slow-motion  modes to make games easier to play by
slowing  them  down.   Gold  Finger  codes  can be saved to disk.  On the
Double  Pro Fighter X, real time save, Gold Finger, and slow-motion modes
are available on the SNES only.
